Hey /gg/,
I want to learn an instrument but I have never touched one all my life and can only allocate around 2 hours per day to it. The prospect of learning and being able to play some of my favourite songs seems very exciting to me.
I‘m debating between bass and guitar. I wouldn’t say that I have a strong preference for either but I’m probably leaning slightly towards guitar.
Is either one recommended to start with and is it easy to switch between if I end up enjoying the hobby and want to try the other?
I’m also planning on visiting a music store to get some advice there but the next one is a decent bit away so I want to have a bit more knowledge before I go.
I watched a couple of the videos linked in the last thread and based on the fact that I enjoy a wide variety of music genres (Jazz, Blues, Bossa Nova, Rock and Metal), I think I should be looking for an electric guitar with a modelling amp?
Would I need anything besides an audio interface for recording to pc?
Do you guys have any other advice for me or things I should be looking out for?

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114407431
As far as learning difficulty goes it really doesn't matter wether you go for bass or guitar, neither of them are easier/more difficult than the other and each one has their own respective skill ceiling. It all depends on your preferred playing style and what "feels" right to you and what type of sound you prefer.
Would I need anything besides an audio interface for recording to pc?
that's basically it

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114407431
Knowledge of one instrument carries over to the other, but the playing technique and general feel of guitar and bass are very different from one another. I'd say guitar is good to start with. For recording you also need a DAW software, such as reaper which is free to try out. A good modelling amp would be a fender mustang amp, imo. I started out with one and served me well over the years.

posts.com:
So since the 00s to now has seen Western pop music transition from rock 'n roll as the standard genre, do you think that progressive rock will see more representation in the dedicated rock scene?

You don't get nearly the disregard or disdain for experimental jazz, classical, bop, folk by traditional fans that you get in rock. I feel that mostly comes from people who grew up with pop and rock like it was peanut butter and jelly and mainly followed pop, so whatever prog they encountered would've been seen as a mistake in rock, rather than a subgenre that didn't pander to their tastes.

Now that rock is increasingly seen as passe in contemporary media, people growing up from the 00s onward are going to be increasingly detached from rock of they only follow what is mainstream (which nearly every music enjoyer does until they hit the age of self-discovery). So people will start treating rock increasingly like jazz and other branches of music that aren't predominant - something people have to seek out to experience rather than be passively exposed and conditioned to, so they go in with curiosity and a more open mind.

I bet you good money that the jojo-fan influx in the '10s was just as much driven by the above as it was memes.

posts.com:
I feel like there's two different crowds when it comes to defining progressive rock.

Traditionalists who claim that progressive rock is a genre with a distinct sound, specifically the bands from the late 1960s and 1970s, and all prog rock and its subgenres from the 80s onwards are derived from, influenced by, and brached out from 70s progressive rock.

And others that claim that "progressive rock" is more of a philosophy or an approach to rock music rather than a genre that started in the 60s and 70s, but isn't bound to a very specific sound and that's why you'll see experimental, noisy, mathy, jazzy, extreme, dissonant, artsy or technical groups with complex time signatures and volatile song structures get labelled prog even if they sound nothing like the 70s bands.

>>114383793
I wouldn’t call the former group traditionalists or purists. The latter philosophy was dominant throughout the emergence and heyday of prog rock and most progressive artists, and I’d also image most of their fans, did not view prog rock so narrowly. Progressive music traditionally meant anything that challenged rules and pushed boundaries, and confining any music to a few small values based on the most superficial stereotypes of its most popular artists would have been counterintuitive to the whole progressive idea in the 1960s and 70s. By definition, there were no “traditionalists” in prog.

>>114392589
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C1JLYJF1zJw

Wish more people knew about Renaldo and The Loaf. It's peak avantgarde music. The two dudes in the band are doctors by profession so their stuff is littered with weird body humor, latin names for diseases, french/german parts, and very intellectual stuff without sounding like pompous assholes because they pull it off with good British humor.

Take for example the second track on this album, it's basically a conversation between a dog and a person
>come here, my dog
>nope, I'm not coming
>don't be silly, come here
>nope, still not coming
while weird whistles and shit are going in the background, just for it to evolve into a kind of medieval tune.

Or take their "Hambu Hodo" -- the whole premise for making this song was that they saw a hamburger&hotdog stand with a sign missing all letters. The band is incredibly lore dense like this with every track having a little story or just quirky silliness behind it.

Also, these two old geezers just reunited and their new stuff is (not as but still) great.

>>114402252
the thing about making sample based beats especially if you're trying to do the 90s boom bap feel is that in terms of melody there is only ever slight variation on a main motif and maybe another element or two for a hook but those would be high passed and eating up very little of the main part of the mix. the way you keep a beat interesting is by throwing in a bunch of unique sounds and textures that play only once or maybe twice throughout the beat once you have it laid out. it takes less effort than you think and once you get the hang of it you can start using it to really build and accentuate energy as opposed to just making things less repetitive.
doing the whole a/b/c verse/chorus/bridge with unique progression for each is not the type of sectioning you tend to see in hip hop.

>>114406121
I work on more than one project, maybe 10 or so.
I just go with the flow, look into this project or the other project. Do what i enjoy right now, either build a pattern, play around with synth, make a melody or play with some effects. Or i start a new project.

There are at least 2 dozen new tracks, but keep myself only active on 8 to 10 tracks. I can finish a track on one day, 8 hours max. Sometimes i produce into the night and when i wake up the next morning i finish the track. But i also have tracks i don't want to finish, i keep them in the production stage on purpose just for fun.

Thats the thing right here, do not start your daw with the expectation to finish a song. Start it with a different intend, see what direction this goes, save it and keep it for later use, or just build some presets for a random vst, make your own samples, etc etc etc....

>>114389053
No. 3 is an odd one so I can understand why you'd feel that. Usually in a concerto grosso, in the first movement there's solo parts for a smaller group of solo instruments and in between those solo parts there's the tutti parts, where the whole orchestra plays a main theme. But in No. 3 it's just a string ensemble (3 violins, 3 violas, 3 cellos and continuo) playing both solo and tutti parts, removing the usual clear loud/soft contrast. In a way it makes it sound more 'Bach-like' with the instruments just 'chugging along' in a Fortspinnung-like manner. There's also the strange second adagio movement that's just one measure (!) long, making the whole piece almost seem like some modernist experiment.

Damn, what did you use to make this one?
That sci fi like synth in seccion 1 sounds very organic. It doesnt have much melodic content yet it manages to stay interesting and keep the attention thorougt the whole duration
Seccion 2 is very relaxing and at the same time it keeps a background tension with the background noise, which blends seemingly with seccion 3, which has nice leads
Seccion 4 has that cool sci fi synth again, and the percussion here is more driven. I also like the fast repeating sounds echoed in various instruments by the middle
Some cool pads in seccion 5 but to me it was the less interesting one for some reason
Seccion 6 has some nice rhythms and a cool sonic atmosphere. The repetitive melody reminds me of a circus, music box or caroussel that then degrades and fades into nothigness

Overall the progression work very well, nothing seems out of place and the transitions are very smooth
Oh and Im really intrigued to know what the scifi synth thing is, the sound and the possibilities it open are very cool

>>114403813
keep in mind that Vai hooked up with him in '79-'80. Frank had been recording since the late-50s and spent the entire '70s touring like a maniac to pay his lawyers in his fight with WB to regain the rights to his music. He took WB to court and was completely in the right that they had broken their contract and ripped him off, but the court didn't care anyway.

Add to that the fact that he was in constant pain ever since he got pushed off the Rainbow stage in late '71. That would make anyone cranky.

Zappa in the '60s was completely different from Zappa in the mid '70s and Zappa in the late '80s.
